  "prompt": "If I saw a crime being perpetrated and I didn't report it, could I go to jail?",
  "response": "Whether you could face legal consequences for not reporting a crime largely depends on the laws in your jurisdiction and the nature of the crime. In many places, there is no legal obligation for an ordinary citizen to report a crime, although there are exceptions.\n\nSome jurisdictions have \"mandatory reporting\" laws that require certain professionals (like teachers, doctors, or social workers) to report specific types of crimes, particularly those involving children or vulnerable individuals. Failing to comply with these laws can result in penalties, including fines or even criminal charges in some cases.\n\nIf you witnessed a serious crime (like a violent crime) and failed to report it, while you are generally not liable for that failure, it might be seen as morally or ethically questionable. However, unless there are specific laws requiring you to report it, it is unlikely you would go to jail simply for not reporting a crime.\n\nIt's always a good idea to consult with a legal expert or local law enforcement if you have specific concerns or if you are unsure about the laws in your area.",
